August 14 at 10:36 AM ·

We need your feedback! Please take the time to complete the Fall Child Care needs survey to help our YMCA finalize our child care plans for the 2020-2021 school year! We are in the planning process of revising our before & after school program as well as launching a Virtual Learning Center for parents who need care during the work day. The answers to this survey will help us finalize those details!! PLEASE SHARE!

LINK TO THE SURVEY: https://s.surveyplanet.com/3yPGFhMsD3

OHS has come to the difficult decision to cancel the 2020 Musical “Big Fish!”. Anyone that paid for tickets before the show was postponed in March can bring those tickets to the gazebo located in the front of the High School on the following dates and times for a full refund:
August 11 12:00-1:00
August 12 3:00-4:00
August 14 5:00-6:00
August 20 4:00-5:00
August 21 4:00-5:00
Please make sure to exercise social distancing and wear face covering when you come to claim your refund. No refund will be granted without the return of tickets.

At a recent press conference, Governor Andrew Cuomo announced that New York State will decide whether schools will reopen in the fall by the first week of August. Districts are required to submit a reopening plan to NYS by July 31st. Starting in the fall, we plan to provide every student with a Chromebook for use at home and at school. As we plan for the various scenarios that could be presented by NYS, we are asking each household to complete this short survey about reliable internet at home.

Please complete one survey per family by Friday, July 17th.
https://forms.gle/svmuraQxSPHxXCyT6

post_text:
Thoughts Wanted!
The OCSD seeks parent feedback as we plan for what learning will look like in the fall. To gather this feedback, we are utilizing a tool called Thoughtexchange. You are asked to respond to one open-ended question, consider and assign stars to some of the ideas shared by others (20 or 30 is ideal), and learn what’s important to the group. Your thoughts and stars are confidential. You can come back as often as you’d like to participate, and in fact, we ask that you do return to star some of the new ideas shared since you first participated. The ratings will help us understand the most important areas to focus on for planning for instruction in the fall.

Please click on the link to participate!

https://my.thoughtexchange.com/812056148

Participation will be open until June 30, 2020.
If you need technical help, please call Thoughtexchange at 1-800-361-9027 ext. 4 or email help@thoughtexchange.com
Thank you in advance for your help and input.
For more information visit: www.thoughtexchange.com

post_text:
On Sunday June 7, 2020, Governor Cuomo announced that he will issue an extension of time for qualified voters to submit their ballots. Pursuant to the executive order, school budget ballots can be accepted by hand delivery through 5pm on June 9th and received by mail through 5 pm on June 16th by the school district. The district office at 565 Sayles Street will be open Monday, June 8 from 7:30 AM- 7:00 PM or on Tuesday, June 9 from 7:30 AM- 5:00 PM.

Additionally, the district was informed neighboring school districts that they have sent ballots to the wrong addresses. Some Oneida City School District residents may have received ballots from a neighboring school district. As a resident of the Oneida City School District, you should use the Oneida City School District ballot to vote.

If you have any questions, please contact the district office at 315-363-2550.

On Sunday June 7, 2020, Governor Cuomo announced that he will issue an extension of time for qualified voters to submit their ballots. Pursuant to the executive order, school budget ballots can be accepted by hand delivery through 5pm on June 9th and received by mail through 5 pm on June 16th by the school district. The district office at 565 Sayles Street will be open Monday, June 8 from 7:30 AM- 7:00 PM or on Tuesday, June 9 from 7:30 AM- 5:00 PM.

Additionally, the district was informed neighboring school districts that they have sent ballots to the wrong addresses. Some Oneida City School District residents may have received ballots from a neighboring school district. As a resident of the Oneida City School District, you should use the Oneida City School District ballot to vote.

If you have any questions, please contact the district office at 315-363-2550.

post_text:
Thoughts Wanted!
The OCSD seeks parent feedback as we plan for what learning will look like in the fall. To gather this feedback, we are utilizing a tool called Thoughtexchange. You are asked to respond to one open-ended question, consider and assign stars to some of the ideas shared by others (20 or 30 is ideal), and learn what’s important to the group. Your thoughts and stars are confidential. You can come back as often as you’d like to participate, and in fact, we ask that you do return to star some of the new ideas shared since you first participated. The ratings will help us understand the most important areas to focus on for planning for instruction in the fall.

Please click on the link to participate!

https://my.thoughtexchange.com/812056148

Participation will be open until June 30, 2020.
If you need technical help, please call Thoughtexchange at 1-800-361-9027 ext. 4 or email help@thoughtexchange.com
Thank you in advance for your help and input.
For more information visit: www.thoughtexchange.com

post_text:
Blood Drive at Oneida High School. Monday, June 8, 2020 10am-3pm in OHS Gym. Please call 1-800-RED CROSS (1-800-733-2767) or visit RedCrossBlood.org
and enter: oneidahighschool to schedule an appointment. All donors will receive a $5 Amazon gift card and a voucher for a cold treat from Stewart’s!

Safety is always a top priority at the American Red Cross and staff may set up the drive differently than normal to accommodate temperature checks, enhanced sanitation, and social distancing guidelines. Donors must wear masks.

Did you know? Oneida High School is the top collecting school for the 2019-2020 year in Madison and Herkimer county? The last blood drive collected 41 units and had 2 first time donors! 41 units can touch up to 123 lives! Also, OHS can earned scholarship funds for total units collected! The scholarship amount will be forwarded to the college/university on behalf of the student for use toward his/her higher education for the fall 2020 semester! Let's keep this good thing going! #WeAreOneida

and enter: oneidahighschool to schedule an appointment. All donors will receive a $5 Amazon gift card and a voucher for a cold treat from Stewart’s!

Safety is always a top priority at the American Red Cross and staff may set up the drive differently than normal to accommodate temperature checks, enhanced sanitation, and social distancing guidelines. Donors must wear masks.

Did you know? Oneida High School is the top collecting school for the 2019-2020 year in Madison and Herkimer county? The last blood drive collected 41 units and had 2 first time donors! 41 units can touch up to 123 lives! Also, OHS can earned scholarship funds for total units collected! The scholarship amount will be forwarded to the college/university on behalf of the student for use toward his/her higher education for the fall 2020 semester! Let's keep this good thing going! #WeAreOneida

post_text:
Absentee Ballots for the Oneida City School District Budget Vote and Election will be mailed on June 3, 2020. As a reminder, ballots must be received by the District Clerk on Tuesday, June 9 by 5:00 PM to be counted. You can mail the ballot or deliver the ballot to the district office at 565 Sayles Street during normal business hours or on Saturday, June 6 from Noon until 4:00 PM, Monday, June 8 from 7:30 AM- 7:00 PM or on Tuesday, June 9 from 7:30 AM- 5:00 PM.

Additionally, the district was informed by a neighboring school district that they have sent ballots to the wrong addresses. Some Oneida City School District residents may have received ballots from a neighboring school district. As a resident of the Oneida City School District, you should use the Oneida City School District ballot to vote.

If you have any questions, please contact the district office at 315-363-2550.

Please click on the link below for more information on the 20-21 Budget Vote. https://www.oneidacsd.org/departments/business_office/2020-21_budget

Mental Health Awareness: This week in our series we are exploring what behaviors and symptoms to watch for in your student. We will identify strategies to manage difficult emotions and ways to talk with your student about their mental health.
We will also discuss normal teenage “hormonal behaviors” versus mental illness, and when to seek professional help.
In addition, we will provide local resources that are available.
Join our Google Meet or dial in by telephone.
Choose the date that works best for you!
Tuesday June 2nd at 7PM:
Meet.google.com/wyf-rfqz-kfb
To join by phone: +1 424-269-9698 PIN 270-586-919#
Thursday June 4th at 11 AM
Meet.google.com/tjy-yzib-rda
To join by phone: +1 475-329-8239 PIN 181 208 110#
We are looking forward to seeing you there!
WE ARE HERE TO SUPPORT YOU AND EACH OTHER. WE ARE #ONEIDASTRONG!

post_text:
SAVE THE DATE!

All of us here at OCSD are missing our students so much! We are excited to announce we will be having a Spirit Drive on Friday April 3rd starting at 11am. We are working on a route to try and incorporate as many of our students as possible. We will be led by local law enforcement and will send you the route later this week so stay tuned!

Here's what we would like you to do:

When you hear the sirens, head to your windows or porches and give us a big wave! We would love to see your faces but to maintain safety you MUST keep social distancing in mind! Please do NOT gather on the street or sidewalks. We do not want families to congregate. Give us your biggest smile and wave to us from a safe distance. Our staff members will also be practicing our social distancing by remaining in our OWN vehicles with our family members while we parade around to visit you.

This is voluntary and you are not mandated to participate in this drive. We cannot wait to see all of your faces! #WeAreOneida

Here's what we would like you to do:

During this current health crisis you may be considered an essential employee who is still required to work.
Child care placement may be available to essential employees who work in health care, are first responders, who work in grocery stores, in transportation, some construction fields, certain non profit agencies and in food or supply distribution fields.

If you believe that you may qualify, please call the Oneida-Herkimer-Madison Child Care Resource Center at 315-223-7850 extension 222.

Thank you to all essential personnel who continue to support our community's safety and health.
Please be safe, and whenever possible, stay at home.

REMINDER: The Oneida City School District will be providing a FREE combined breakfast and lunch grab-and-go meal starting Tuesday, March 17 - Monday, April 13 Monday-Friday to all families with students currently enrolled at Oneida CSD.

If you have not done so already, please sign up online at oneidacsd.org or call the district office 315-363-2550, ext. 3. to sign up for the grab-and-go meal.
If you already signed up, there is no need to sign up again.

Please provide the name of the person who will be picking up the grab-and-go meal, number of meals needed, and the school building they would like to pick up at.

Pick up time for the grab and go meal will be from 8:45-9:45am.

Did you know? When the district sends out a robo call, text, or email, many messages don't go through? Check your settings!
Any time your contact information has changed, you are encouraged to download the SchoolMessenger App or visit the website https://go.schoolmessenger.com and follow the steps to change how you would like to be contacted. Alternatively, you can contact the student registration office during school hours to update your contact records. Lori Cimpi in student registration can be reached at 315-361-6072.
Remember, SchoolMessenger is not just for delays! Oneida uses SchoolMessenger to communicate on a mass scale for any school emergencies, school-related cancellations, non-emergency community engagement events and most recently, how the district is responding to the coronavirus.📞

Any time your contact information has changed, you are encouraged to download the SchoolMessenger App or visit the website https://go.schoolmessenger.com and follow the steps to change how you would like to be contacted. Alternatively, you can contact the student registration office to update your contact records. Lori Cimpi in student registration can be reached at 315-361-6072.
Remember, SchoolMessenger is not just for delays! Oneida uses SchoolMessenger to communicate on a mass scale for any school emergencies, school-related cancellations, non-emergency community engagement events and most recently, how the district is responding to the coronavirus. 📞

Oneida Student and Alpine Skier Alex Tooker has qualified for the U19 USSA Eastern US Region Finals, March 19-22, 2020 at Gore Mountain in North Creek, NY.

Alex was selected to represent NYS (1 of 12 men) at the USSA Eastern Regional High School Championships this past weekend at Cannon Mountain in New Hampshire.

This photo is from an event earlier in the season at Bristol Mountain Ski Resort. Alex earned an overall 1st Place Finish in Giant Slalom.

Join us in wishing Alex good luck in North Creek! #WeAreOneida

post_text:
Students in Julie Koelsch's 6th grade science class have been working on quite the project! They are exploring heat and energy concepts.

They discussed how heat energy transfers- focusing on a large block of ice in the front of the room. What is making it melt? The children then drew the answer to the question on their science table tops with chalk. They used arrows and diagrams to show how heat energy is transferred through convection, conduction and radiation.

Over the next few classes they brainstormed how they could slow down the melting process.

Everyone starts with the same size piece of ice, and they can use materials from home or from the classroom. Materials that they cannot use are coolers, insulated cups or thermos.

The students really stepped up to the challenge! #WeAreOneida #MiddleSchoolCounts

Help us kick off Music in Our Schools Month! 🎤🎹👨‍🎤🎼🥁

Tomorrow night - Thursday, February 27th - Choral Night Concert at 7:00 pm at Oneida HS in the auditorium. This concert will feature our 5th Grade Select All-City Chorus, the OSMS 8th Grade Chorus and the HS Chamber Choir.
Monday, March 2nd - Band Night Concert at 7:00 pm at Oneida HS in the auditorium. This concert will feature our 5th Grade Select All-City Band, OSMS 6th Grade Band, 7th & 8th Grade Bands Combined and the OHS Concert Band and Wind Ensemble Combined.

In addition, our jazz bands will be attending the New Hartford and Oneida Jazz Festivals this year!

post_text: The winning team for the fall session of the OHS-OSMS stock market challenge was from Mr. Ottaviano's 7th period class at OSMS. Team Ramsey's Kitchen beat out 17 other teams. The teams were from OSMS, OHS, the District Office, other teachers and administrators from OSMS. Each team was given 100,000 and had to invest in 4 stocks. The winning team made 121,577 over the duration of the game.

post_text:
Wow! Our district has some great thoughts about their hopes for the future of the Oneida City School District. Thank you so much for your thoughts and ratings.

The results of the exchange about our hopes for the school district were really exciting. This image is word cloud with the results of the exchange.

We found the theme with the most comments was Social Emotional Learning (SEL) and the theme with the most stars was Graduation Rate.

Please use this link to review the results in depth: https://my.thoughtexchange.com/report/1b2bc473947d929f31954134c654eea8

We are excited to launch several new Thought Exchanges this winter and spring that are based on the results of the “Hope’ exchange. We look forward to your thoughts about our school district. #WeAreOneida

post_text: The MVCC Drone class at Oneida HS is learning about electricity and electronic components. They are reading schematic diagrams and identifying the parts as they build automated cars that can detect and follow a path. Students are also learning to solder small components as well. This tedious task is in preparation for building and maintaining drones that will be used in competition and through out the year. #WeAreOneida #OneidaSTEAM

post_text: Mrs. Nestler, a third grade teacher at Durhamville, and the Coach of Oneida's Varsity Girl's Basketball Team, celebrated her birthday yesterday. Mrs. Nestler was unaware that one of the girls on her team had previously reached out to Durhamville and together we worked to give Mrs. Nestler a little birthday surprise! Nine of the students in her class and their families showed up to the Varsity Girls Basketball home game last night to show their support and to wish Mrs, Nestler a Happy Birthday!

post_text: The photography classes at Oneida HS are learning how to light paint. The technique uses the camera sensor like a blank canvas, and light becomes the paint. The trick is to create light paint brushes, simple items that student use to control how the light is applied to the camera. The results can be very creative, and a lot of fun! #WeAreOneida #OneidaArt
